attributes.descriptionHtml:
Helloooooooo!! My name is Smoke. My foster mom likes to make up songs about me, and sometimes she calls me Smokey, Smokey Bones and Smokestack.

Life for me hasn't always been great.....

My last person kept me chained on a very short chain in the kitchen or crated, unless they wanted to use me for a stud dog. Then, they stopped feeding me. I don't really know don't know why they did that to me.
One day a lady calling herself a Guardian came and took me on a car ride. My owner told the Guardian that the neighbor had poisoned me, so they took me to the doctor. I was so happy to break free from those chains. Truth is, I just needed food, and love.
The next day, I met my foster mom. Although she loves me very much, she tells me that I can't stay with her forever. She promised me that she would love me until my new person finds me.   I have never really had the opportunity to be a puppy, so now.....I am making up for lost time.
I love my foster kids, but I I'm going to need some time and patience so a home with older kids would be best. My biggest downfall is that I just get too excited and want to jump. I loved my foster brothers though (3yrs & 11yrs) and am very protective.

I need a patient person/family that can give me lots of exercise and is willing to set boundaries and continue to work on my manners. Im a big boy and I like to go full speed.   I am not really a fan of smaller animals, like cats. They look like toys, but they don't like when I play with them. I like some other medium to large easy going dogs but would require a slow introduction.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Louie's adoption donation is $300 has been neutered, microchipped, received his rabies, distemper/parvo, bordetella and flu vaccinations, tested negative for heartworms and has started on prevention, as well as flea protection. He also has had a dental cleaning.

Louie was surrendered to a shelter for unknown reasons. Upon rescuing him, it was discovered he had a heart murmur. After a consultation with a cardiologist, Louie was diagnosed with several heart defects. Surgery was being considered until he was then diagnosed with a possible liver shunt. It was then decided to not do surgery. Louie's life expectancy is really unknown but with known medical issues he has been stable with us and has done very well.  He had been with a foster home but unfortunately she could no longer care for him.  Since he has been stable with regular monitoring, we are making available for adoption.

Louie has personality plus! He is a "talker" and is so enthusiastic about life! Squeaky toys are his favorite. Louie  is also a little love bug and loves to cuddle with his people. He will snuggle right under your chin so he can lay his head on your heart. Louie is a "typical " miniature poodle as he can be protective. Louie loves food and has no problem trying to take food from any other dog so he is best to feed by himself. A home with older children is preferred. . 

Louie does very well on house training if kept on a schedule. He likes to be outside but he is not a long walker as he tires easily. This little guy gets along with other dogs, but does do better with females than he does males. Louie is just adorable and anyone would fall in love with this lil guy.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Hi furiends! I'm Mango and my partner in crime, Mia.

Here's a little about us. Our first owner died suddenly and we were left all alone. Then we were rescued and went to a very nice Foster family, where our Foster Mom treated us like her very own babies. And then one day,  we met and were adopted by a nice family. We lived with them for about a year. Due to unforeseen circumstances they had to bring us back to DASH  We are staring to age so we would love our very own human(s) we can Love, Snuggle and Cuddle with and take long naps together. We like to follow you wherever you go but we won't disturb your peace and quiet, as we promise we rarely ever bark. Not to mention, we don't mind being crated when you're away, or take us with you, we love going for car rides. We potty outside as long as we are taken outside frequently. We still enjoy going for short walks.

Our top 3 favorite things in life are food, big cozy beds, and sunshine! We don't like the cold weather, snow, or rain! I must share with you, that we can't hear very well. We use to follow our (first)Foster Mom's hand signals instead of her voice. And I (Mango) had to have my right eye removed after I was rescued due to a bad infection. But it doesn't phase me. Mia doesn't like to be picked up but she always needs help to get up on the couch. We get along well with other doggies and kids who don't topple all over us. I'm not sure whether we like cats or not, we haven't had any kitty friends before. But we're so laid back, sweet, and affectionate. We're really easy pups to care for but we will need daily brushing and will need to see a groomer every month or every other month to keep us nice and handsome and pretty.

We can't wait to finally have a FOREVER family!!

www.dashanimalrescue.org
Dashrescue00@gmail.com

Ringo just might be the most photogenic cat in the FIV+ Room. Just look how he poses so perfectly! Although he doesn’t have his own Instagram account currently, he’s very willing to be featured on yours. He’s a friendly and chill guy who likes looking out the window. (DOB 8/14/16)    If you are interested in adopting me, please fill out an online adoption application at https://colonycats.org/adoption_app.html  to expedite the process. Due to the large number of inquiries received, we are unable to respond to emails quickly.

Feline Immunodeficiency Virus positive cats can live normal lives both in quality and duration. They do take special care in terms of monitoring them for signs of infection.  FIV can be passed from cat to cat via deep bite wounds, but not from casual contact so positive cats can live with negative cats without the fear of spreading FIV as long as they get along and are spayed/neutered. For more information about FIV – feline immunodeficiency virus visit this website: https://bestfriends.org/resources/fiv-cats-faqs-feline-immunodeficiency-virus We currently have sponsorship funds for FIV+ cat adoptions.  Speak to a Colony Cats representative about this.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
This big fluff ball is our golden boy Cheb. Having retired from a lifetime of farm duties, Cheb is looking for a quiet home to rest his bones, and to enjoy all the love he deserves. Although Cheb has not lived inside a house his whole life, he has excellent house manners and is a pyrfect gentleman in his foster home. He is not quite sure what to make of the stairs indoors yet, but he seems to navigate the ones outdoors with ease. Cheb likes to spend most of his day napping in various parts of the house, being the most pyrfect work from home companion. He likes to stretch his legs in the afternoons, preferably a nice stroll around the neighborhood just to make sure everything is in order. Cheb is the definition of a gentle giant - he gets along well with laid back dogs but can get grumpy with felines so we recommend no cats. He is a tad shy, given his limited interactions with people in his past, but he truly adores a good scratch behind the ears and a nice long belly rub :) If you enjoy a quiet lifestyle and have plenty of love to spare, Cheb may be the pyrfect companion for you!

NGPR Pooch Profile

Name: Cheb in PA

Age: 11 yrs 4 mos old as of June 2021

Color: White

Dew Claws: Double

Estimated Adult Weight: 90 lbs

Current Location: NGPR approved foster in Palmyra, PA

Medical: Neutered, dewormed, up-to-date on vaccinations and currently on flea, tick, and heartworm preventative. This dog travels with an Interstate Health Certificate required by the USDA confirming that all the above criteria have been met.

Housebroken: Yes

Can be Placed With: Other calm dogs, older kids, no cats.

Fencing: Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Fees: Adoption fee TBD.

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

If you can't foster or adopt at this time, please consider helping our Neediest Cases.

Please visit our ADOPTION CENTER to complete the application form and learn more about Pyrs and our adoption process. Thanks.
About Us: National Great Pyrenees Rescue (NGPR) is not a shelter. We are a not-for-profit, tax-exempt coalition of Pyr rescuers and rescue groups. We save Pyrs and Pyr mixes across the country and place them in approved foster homes so we know how they will interact with your family. Please consider adopting or fostering. Every dog who is fostered or adopted makes room for another Pyr coming out of a kill shelter. Prior to adoption, NGPR dogs are fostered for a minimum of two weeks (usually more), spayed or neutered and fully vetted. Dogs coming from out of area are certified with a USDA health certificate before going to their new homes. Our rescuers adhere to the highest placement standards and will take back any dog whose adoption does not succeed. Visit www.nationalpyr.org to learn more about us, our mission and our breed.
More Information: Questions? The fastest way to learn more about a dog is to fill out the application form below. If you call or e-mail you are reducing your chances of adopting this animal as we direct our time and energy to first serving those who apply. For more information about our adoption process please visit our adoption information page.
Want to help but can’t adopt now? You can make a tax-exempt donation by visiting our donation page.
This exceptional Great Pyrenees dog has been selected for sponsorship by National Great Pyrenees Rescue (NGPR)We have many Pyrs and Pyr mixes who need homes and not all of them are posted. You can see more of these beautiful dogs by clicking on Adoptable Dogs.

Love this breed? NGPR now has a Rescue Store where your purchase goes to help our rescue dogs and neediest cases.

Frosty is a beautiful, petite collie. She had a rough past but has blossomed in her foster home and is looking forward to finding her forever home. She was an outside dog, but quickly learned house manners, is house trained, is a quiet girl, can be trusted in the home without being crated (she will sleep in the crate but doesn't like to be "put" in it), is good with other dogs in the household and with cats. She loves mealtimes and does a happy trot as she watches her dish come to her spot to eat. Frosty has been fully vetted but she intermittently has digestive issues and will need to remain on a prescription diet, be fed 3-4 times a day and take a daily medication. The prescription food and medication run about $100 per month altogether.

She's a cautious gal and takes a little time to warm up to new dogs and people so she would enjoy a home with just adults or with older children who are not rambunctious. But, once she get to know you she is happy to cuddle and watch tv on the sofa. a little nudge to your hand lets you know she'd really like some petting. Outside Frosty is happy to be chasing, wrestling and playing with the rest of her dog family. Is Frosty the one for you?

 

The adoption fee for Frosty is $300.00

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Meet Groucho! Named due to his 'Groucho Marx' mustache.  Groucho loves to play and he has a high prey drive.  Don't even think about taking his toys.  He gets comfortable in new environments pretty easily.  He's  not a fan of rambunctuous dogs as he was previously in a home with one and he was not a happy camper.  But he gets along fabulously with other cats and humans.  He's very loving and playful.

DOB 3/16/19 Groucho is neutered, microchipped, up to date on vaccines, FL negative.  Groucho is FIV+.  He can live with FIV- cats as he does very well with other cats who are also fixed.

If you are interested in adopting me, please fill out an online adoption application at https://colonycats.org/adoption_app.html  to expedite the process. Due to the large number of inquiries received, we are unable to respond to emails quickly.

Feline Immunodeficiency Virus positive cats can live normal lives both in quality and duration. They do take special care in terms of monitoring them for signs of infection.  FIV can be passed from cat to cat via deep bite wounds, but not from casual contact so positive cats can live with negative cats without the fear of spreading FIV as long as they get along and are spayed/neutered. For more information about FIV – feline immunodeficiency virus visit this website: https://bestfriends.org/resources/fiv-cats-faqs-feline-immunodeficiency-virus

Meet Spike!

Spike takes a little bit to warm up, but loves to play like the puppy he is. He is very timid and skittish to fast movements. He has not been around children since coming to the rescue. Spike loves to play with dogs of all sizes, but also loves to try and play with his humans. He also likes to get in the pool and try to swim around while someone holds him. He’s very food motivated and loves treats or anything someone is eating/ drinking.
Spike is potty trained though since he’s still a puppy he sometimes makes mistakes in his crate. He is partially crate trained and sleeps through the night without a peep. If left unsupervised outside of a crate, he will chew things up. Spike also likes to smile! He will wiggle up to you and bare his teeth to ask for pets.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Doug is a cuddly 8 month old mixed breed puppy, who is ready to find his forever home!

 

Doug ended up at a shelter as a very young puppy, emaciated and in horrible condition. He had a mildly lame leg initially, which was diagnosed as a growth plate fracture. After a couple months of crate rest, he was as good as new, and his leg needs no further care. You'd never know he ever had an issue by the way he gallops! 


Doug is a recent graduate of our prison training program and now knows his basic commands. He's also crate trained and fully house trained. He's SUPER sweet, loves to be affectionate with his humans, and LOVES to play with other dogs. He's curious about cats, but not aggressive. He's also very good with kids, but is still puppy-like in a lot of ways, so if your kids are experienced with dogs, then they'd be fine. 

 

If you are interested in adopting Doug, please submit an application on our website, www.prodogsohio.org/adoptables. He's been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, and his adoption fee is $300. 

 

Please note, we only schedule meet and greets with approved applicants, as we are all volunteers and do not have a facility for you to visit our dogs. If you have questions about Doug that are not answered in this bio, please email info@prodogsohio.org. Responses to inquiries received via third party sites often go to spam folders and delay our ability to reach you.

She is a little shy with new people, but is so sweet and affectionate once she is comfortable. She has been living in a foster home with other cats and three Great Danes. While the kittens were with her, she had shown some dislike for other cats, but we believe once she is settled in and no longer needing to protect them, she should adjust fairly quickly. She does however like the dogs, even the feisty puppy!! Calypso would do best in a home without small children just because she is a little shy, but would do great with older kids, dogs, and potentially cats. This girl just wants love and attention, if you think that's you, please fill out an application on this sweet girl!!! Calypso  is spayed, microchipped, FL/FIV negative and up to date on vaccines. Bobo’s adoption donation is $375 and he is being fostered in Northeast Ohio.  He has been neutered, microchipped, received his rabies, distemper/parvo, bivalent canine influenza, and Bordetella vaccines, tested negative for heartworms and started on heartworm/flea/tick prevention. He has also had a dental cleaning.  Bobo requires a home with a strong veterinary history.

Bobo was surrendered by his previous owner when he didn't get along with another dog in the home and the owner stated that he was aggressive toward another dog in the home who was first aggressive towards him. Thankfully, someone advocated for him and his foster mom has not seen evidence of aggression. He most likely will thrive in a home with no young children under the age of 10 years old and with a dog that is of calmer temperament. His forever pawrents must also be comfortable with his growls because he is a talkative dog - albeit all bark and no bite. He just likes to "trash talk" He favors men and possibly older women. His foster mum says, "He's so funny because he seems to not like me too much because he growls at me the most. He'll come and growl when I put ear drops or his belly band but won't walk away from me and will instead lean in for scratchies. He's very loving, sweet and a really good cuddler. He's hefty so he's extra nice to cuddle with. He's got these beautiful, soulful eyes that seem to speak to you and everyone in the house loves him so so much."  Bobo is on a special diet due to allergies and must remain on that diet. Bobo has done really well with housetraining on a schedule. He enjoys car rides and walks with his foster bros.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
It’s tough to pick an example of when Stewart is at his cutest but it’s probably how, after a week of getting to know his foster family, he started getting the zoomies when he sees them in the morning, or his tiny tail wags when you call him Stu-Stu.

Stu, as he's affectionately known, doesn’t have any aggressive tendencies at all, to the degree that he doesn’t like tug and fetch is still a bit scary for him, but he is still scared of a lot of things and needs gentle repetition to work through those fears. He loves running around and (when he gets very comfortable) will do an impressive juke and spin move to show he’s only pretending to be scared.

Stu is fully house trained, kennel trained, and knows his basic commands. He’s a quick learner and really lights up doing tricks, and would do great in a home that kept up his training. He’s exceptionally curious, which is a great sign for overcoming fears because he’s willing to try hard things (the first time he went in a car he was panicked blind, and now he’ll get himself in and out of the car).

Stu is a really exceptionally wonderful dog, but because he’s still learning that people can be kind, he needs a home with people who are chill if he doesn’t do something for them immediately. He cannot go to a home where he is only one person’s pet. He needs a home where everyone in the family will pet him gently whenever they get close, speak nicely to him, and use positive reinforcement. In that home, Stu will quickly come out of his shell and be an absolutely amazing member of the family. Stu would be happiest in a home with a confident, non-aggressive dog to imitate and run around with. He can go to a home with kids of any age or cats, but only if the adults in the home are good about setting boundaries and teaching their kids to be gentle.

If you are interested in adopting Stewart, please submit an application on our website, www.prodogsohio.org/adoptables. His adoption fee is $300 and a fenced yard is non-negotiable for Stewart.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Welcome Screech! 
 
Screech is a 1 year old mixed breed, whose look is just as unique as his personality! He's been hanging out at the shelter for a few months and they thought he'd be a better candidate for adoption if he moved to a foster home. They were spot on and he's currently thriving in our foster home! 
 
This hunky guy weighs about 45 lbs and is full grown. He knows basic commands: sit, down, stay, and leave it. Screech loves to take walks and play outside. He is potty trained and will let you know when he needs to go out, and is also crate trained.
 
Screech is energetic and jumps when he gets excited so he would do best in a home with older children. Screech also will chew on toys/clothes/shoes if he has access to them, so crating is non-negotiable until he's past his early years. He redirects well and will “leave it” when told. He may not do well with cats because he enjoys chasing them, but he hasn't hurt one. 
 
Screech is food motivated and will need a home that will continue to work on manners with him. He is eligible to go to our prison program when we have an opening in the future, which an adopter can take advantage of after adoption. 
 
If you are interested in adopting Screech, please submit an application on our website, www.prodogsohio.org/adoptables. His adoption fee is $300. 
 
Please note we only schedule meet and greets with approved adopters, so you must have an approved application on file to meet Screech. We do not have a facility where all of our dogs are housed; all meet and greets are scheduled with foster families. 
 
The best way to reach us with questions that are not answered in this listing is by email at adoptions@prodogsohio.org. Replies to inquiries we receive through third party sites typically go to Spam folders, so please keep an eye out for our replies!

Qtip loves to use his little voice to let you know if someone is at the door, or across the street on a walk but he is very friendly when meeting new friends (human or canine). He hasn't been trained much on a leash but he loves to go for walks to sniff. He knows to sit and his name, but he would like his new family to teach him more tricks as long as they provide yummy treats. Qtip is potty trained and crate trained and will bark at you if he needs to use the potty. 

Qtip would be great in an only pup home or a home with other dogs. Once he learns the dog dynamic he adjusts pretty easily to any home situation. Qtip is such a sweet, loving, happy dog and is ready for his forever family to love him for the rest of his life!

attributes.name: Ohio House Rabbit Rescue, Inc.
attributes.adoptionProcess:
We require that all of our rabbits live indoors in a minimum of a 4x4 space or free range inside the home, be fed high-quality pellets, unlimited hay and a daily salad and given plenty of attention and exercise.  Adopters also commit to providing regular veterinary care.  All rabbits are spayed/neutered before being adopted.  In addition, the primary caregiver must be an adult. If the adopter cannot care for their rabbit, they must return it to Ohio House Rabbit Rescue.

To adopt a rabbit, potential adopters must first fill out an application for a rabbit they are interested in. Then, they are interviewed by OHRR Adoption Coordinators. If their application is approved and interview is successful, they sign a contract stating that they understand our expectations for the care of their rabbit(s), that they will notify Ohio House Rabbit Rescue when the rabbit dies, and that they understand that OHRR reserves the right to remove the rabbit if we feel his/her life is endangered or if there is a violation of the adoption policy.  OHRR delivers all rabbits to the home of the adopter to help the adopter set-up their new rabbitâs space and help with additional rabbit-proofing.  This also helps OHRR to ensure that all rabbit housing is appropriate.  

To adopt a single rabbit the fee is $40.  A bonded pair is $60.
attributes.about:
Ohio House Rabbit Rescue is a 501(c)3 nonprofit organization dedicated rescuing and adopting indoor pet rabbits. Our mission is to establish and operate a Center for rescued abandoned pet rabbits, offer a robust adoption program and provide educational resources and programming on the proper care of rabbits as indoor companions.  OHRR envisions a community where all pet rabbits live indoors as companions and have access to a proper diet, habitat, and regular veterinary care for the duration of their life.

OHRR was founded in 2009 by longtime rabbit owner, Beverly May.  After realizing that over 900 rabbits were offered for surrender each year in Central Ohio alone, Beverly decided that Ohio needed a rescue and adoption center for rabbits.  OHRR began with an extensive network of foster homes in order to begin rescuing rabbits and to build community support. In 2013, OHRR opened the Ohio House Rabbit Adoption Center, which is the first rescue and adoption center in Ohio that is exclusively for rabbits. In 2013, we founds homes for over 70 bunnies.

In addition to our adoptions program, OHRR hosts Midwest BunFest, the largest rabbit-related exposition in the Eastern United States. BunFest includes shopping from various small animal supply vendors, the Bunny Spa with nail trips and grooming, Bunny Glamour Shots pet photography, a chance to interact with rabbit rescues across the Midwest, and also has over 10 education sessions from nationally recognized veterinarians and certified rabbit educators. In 2012, OHRR developed the Fix-a-Bun (FAB) Low-Cost Spay/Neuter program that provides assistance in paying for spay/neuter surgery for rabbits in Ohio, and the program has helped many families pay for spay/neuter surgery. Further, OHRR attends adoption events at local pet supply stores on an ongoing basis and hosts community fundraisers quarterly. OHRR also provides email and telephone support to rabbit owners across Ohio and in other states.
